Anonymous Wed 23 Dec 2020 14:22:14 No.34945255 Report
Quoted By: >>34945376
>>34945137
I am generally a proponent of greentext as a style, but this, to a degree. It's considerably easier to not fuck up greentext because it encourages active voice writing and makes it more natural to keep the pace up. It's also more flexible when it comes to literary devices.

Greentext is basically free verse prose. I strongly recommend it if you're having a hard time finding your "voice" or are just curious to fuck around with a more flexible structure. Try to avoid getting too entrenched, though.

You sit down and do it. Simple as. People seem to think there's some secret to doing it, but all you can do is force yourself into doing it. Sure there are some things that can help, like thinking about the people who are waiting for your content, getting a beta reader, doing a consistent word count a day, or even removing all distractions, but in the end it all comes down to you.

Sit down. Tap away at your keyboard. Come back to it later. Fix it. Tap some more. That's the key. You can do it!

>>34950596
Dude, it's your project, if you think that your story is told well in the greentext format, than there isn't a need to change. I dropped my opinion as a hot take because I wanted to see if anyone would bite the bait.
If you want to switch to prose, however, I would break up blocks of lines into paragraphs first. Convert block by block into prose, and play around with the placement of details until you get something that flows well. The biggest adjustment you'll have to make is probably the tenses. Greentext allows you to play much looser than you can in actual prose, so this might be the toughest change. You also want to cut down on memes or "Chanisms" when converting a piece.
>ohfuck.jpg
is pretty standard fare for greentext but doesn't translate well to prose. It may take a few tries to adequately convey the emotions of your characters, but facial expression, body language, and internal and external dialogue are good ways to sell it when you don't have access to "reaction image shorthand".

When you first start out, don't try to draw from memory, always use photographic references so you can build up a visual library. There's no shame in using references to draw something, it helps you get acquainted with the human form and proportions of the human body. It'll come in handy even when drawing anthros anon. I recommend you start using them as much as possible, and try to find artists whose styles of art you enjoy, and try to replicate that within your own art. That's what I've been doing to improve since I started drawing.
